Nothing.

39:57.103 --> 39:58.562
Don't be shy.

39:59.063 --> 40:00.189
Did you orgasm?

40:00.272 --> 40:01.690
Did I orgasm?

40:01.774 --> 40:02.775
What?

40:03.359 --> 40:06.821
-I can't believe you're from New York.
-You could be faking, right?

40:07.071 --> 40:08.906
You can't tell if a woman is faking?

40:08.989 --> 40:11.158
I can't even tell
if a woman is interested.

40:11.826 --> 40:14.954
But you can tell if somebody's lying,
like a suspect.

40:15.037 --> 40:16.747
That is not the same thing.

40:16.831 --> 40:18.707
-Pretend I'm a suspect.
-[scoffs]

40:18.791 --> 40:21.293
Use your powers of deduction, Agent Ford.

40:21.377 --> 40:22.420
[sighs]

40:22.503 --> 40:26.257
How can you figure out the criminal mind
if you can't figure out your girlfriend?

40:27.675 --> 40:28.926
Are you my girlfriend?

40:29.343 --> 40:32.847
Wait. Is this another of those things
you just can't tell?

40:33.389 --> 40:35.599
I don't know. Are you?

40:36.183 --> 40:38.769
What do you need,
an exchange of rings over milkshakes?

40:38.853 --> 40:40.771
I just didn't want to presume anything.

40:41.230 --> 40:43.649
Really, Holden,
sometimes you're like a monk.

40:44.525 --> 40:47.570
Surely people in law enforcement
shouldn't be so naive.

40:47.653 --> 40:49.238
Does it make you uncomfortable...

40:50.531 --> 40:52.032
sleeping with a federal agent?

40:52.116 --> 40:53.701
[laughs]

40:54.785 --> 40:56.203
Where did that come from?

40:58.747 --> 41:00.082
Does it turn you on?

41:01.625 --> 41:02.793
Not at all.

41:08.090 --> 41:09.467
Then why are you with me?

41:10.801 --> 41:12.303
You're smart.

41:14.930 --> 41:16.474
You're nice.

41:17.349 --> 41:18.559
[mutters] Okay.

41:19.727 --> 41:21.896
What? Those are good things.

41:24.732 --> 41:26.817
And you're devastating.

41:26.901 --> 41:28.235
[Holden chuckles]

41:28.319 --> 41:29.445
Well, thank you.

41:30.237 --> 41:31.655
Oh, come on, you're not leaving.

41:32.907 --> 41:34.283
I have to get up early.

41:34.867 --> 41:36.577
Tomorrow's the first day of school.

41:37.161 --> 41:42.917
[man on radio]  Ninety-nine plus KFMH,
Muscatine, Davenport in Iowa Central...

41:43.000 --> 41:45.169
[changing stations]

41:46.378 --> 41:49.840
[Toto's "Hold the Line" playing]

41:53.928 --> 41:55.012
♪ Hold the line ♪

41:58.849 --> 42:01.685
[Tench] Today might be a baptism of fire.
They're gonna be on edge.

42:01.769 --> 42:03.354
-Just follow my lead.
-What happened?

42:03.771 --> 42:05.898
They caught a big case
and they're spooked.

42:05.981 --> 42:07.441
Don't talk to any reporters.

42:08.150 --> 42:11.237
And please, for God's sake,
don't say we're from the FBI.

42:14.865 --> 42:18.452
♪ It's not in the words
That you told me, girl ♪

42:24.208 --> 42:27.169
Excuse me, gentlemen.
I'm from the  Fairfield Chronicle.

42:27.253 --> 42:29.380
You gentlemen are from the FBI,
is that right?

42:29.463 --> 42:31.048
How are things with the Jeffries case?

42:31.131 --> 42:32.758
No idea what you're talking about.

42:32.841 --> 42:34.426
The Jeffries case. Ada Jeffries.

42:34.510 --> 42:37.596
-You can come back for the rest.
-The woman found behind the church.

42:37.680 --> 42:40.266
-We're here for something else.
-The woman and her little boy.

42:40.349 --> 42:41.725
We're instructors.

42:41.809 --> 42:43.269
Are you from the Methodist church?

42:43.352 --> 42:45.354
Do we look like
we're from the Methodist church?

42:45.437 --> 42:46.397
Yes.

42:46.939 --> 42:47.940
Make a hole.

42:49.525 --> 42:50.693
Good to see ya.

42:51.902 --> 42:54.113
[Tench] Motive, means, opportunity.

42:54.196 --> 42:57.575
The three pillars of criminal
investigation for the last century.

42:58.158 --> 43:01.704
But it's 1977,
and suddenly motive is elusive.

43:03.372 --> 43:04.748
What, why, who.

43:05.291 --> 43:08.168
"What happened?"
"Why did it happen that way?"

43:08.252 --> 43:10.087
Which should lead to: "Who did it?"

43:11.130 --> 43:14.258
A person is murdered.
Not sexually assaulted, not robbed.

43:14.633 --> 43:16.677
But the body is mutilated posthumously.

43:17.177 --> 43:19.847
The question is not only
why did the killer do it,

43:19.930 --> 43:22.016
but why did the killer do it this way?

43:23.100 --> 43:27.187
We are now talking about... psychology.

43:30.232 --> 43:33.193
[clears throat] When I'm involved
in a hostage negotiation,

43:33.277 --> 43:35.529
the perpetrator is standing
right in front of me,

43:35.613 --> 43:38.866
but I have to gauge
how much destruction he's capable of,

43:39.366 --> 43:43.621
what in his background or personal life
that could've triggered today's standoff.

43:43.704 --> 43:45.247
Some people are just crazy, right?

43:45.789 --> 43:47.958
Crazy in that they have no reason
for what they do?

43:48.042 --> 43:49.376
-Yeah.
-[Holden] Okay.

43:49.460 --> 43:53.922
But keep in mind, often, this crazy person
has never done anything like this before.

43:54.006 --> 43:55.799
Something just... flips.

43:56.383 --> 43:58.260
-Like a switch.
-Good, a switch.

43:58.761 --> 44:00.220
Anybody know what flips it?

44:01.180 --> 44:03.474
-Getting fired?
-Fired. Yes.

44:03.557 --> 44:04.933
-Getting dumped.
-[Holden] Absolutely.

44:05.017 --> 44:07.227
A romantic breakup is a top trigger.

44:07.728 --> 44:11.523
When we know who the criminal is,
we can understand what set him off.

44:11.607 --> 44:13.817
In a homicide situation,
we do the inverse.

44:14.234 --> 44:18.572
We ask, "What happened?
Why did it happen that way?"

44:18.656 --> 44:20.783
Which narrows the search for who did it.

44:21.283 --> 44:24.578
But what if our killer
is someone who's not rational?

44:31.251 --> 44:33.170
Why do we behave the way we do?

44:34.713 --> 44:38.801
It's a question asked by poets,
and philosophers, and theologians

44:38.884 --> 44:40.511
since time immemorial.

44:40.928 --> 44:44.765
The playground of Shakespeare,
Dostoyevsky, Freud.

44:44.848 --> 44:48.435
The stuff of  Crime and Punishment
and  Beyond the Pleasure Principal.

44:49.687 --> 44:53.941
The greatest minds in history have been
fascinated by the vagaries of behavior.

44:56.485 --> 45:01.490
So, in a case where we can't immediately
divine a motive, we shouldn't panic.

45:02.199 --> 45:04.034
It's a riddle, but it can be solved.

45:04.118 --> 45:07.996
It's complex, but... it's human.

45:10.290 --> 45:12.292
-[quiet muttering]
-Thank you, Holden.

45:13.460 --> 45:15.504
That was very... illuminating.

45:15.587 --> 45:18.549
[quiet laughter, chatter]

45:18.632 --> 45:21.176
So what the hell's
Beyond the Pleasure Principle?

45:21.260 --> 45:24.096
-By Freud?
-[man] So this is about sex?

45:24.179 --> 45:26.765
Actually, it's where he looks
for human impulses beyond sex,

45:26.849 --> 45:28.892
-specifically the death drive.
-[man 2] What's that?

45:28.976 --> 45:31.937
-Something my kid does with a stick shift.
-[laughter]

45:32.020 --> 45:34.481
Freud suggests that there's
an innate desire for destruction,

45:34.565 --> 45:36.859
based on the propensity for matter
to return--

45:36.942 --> 45:38.902
-What does this have to do with motive?
-[Holden] Well...

45:39.319 --> 45:43.323
we've always looked at motive
as need or greed, right?

45:43.407 --> 45:46.285
-Guy steals a TV to sell it to buy drugs.
-[Holden] Exactly.

45:46.368 --> 45:49.371
But let's say, while he's at it,
he steals your wife's panties, too.

45:49.455 --> 45:51.165
If he stole my wife's panties,
I'd be amazed.

45:51.248 --> 45:53.792
-[laughter]
-[Holden] Well, he's not selling those.

45:53.876 --> 45:56.170
So why does he do it?
Is it merely prurient?

45:56.253 --> 45:58.755
He could be motivated by something
he doesn't even understand.

45:58.839 --> 46:01.091
Our new quest, like Freud,

46:01.175 --> 46:04.761
is to look beyond what we assume
are obvious impulses.

46:04.845 --> 46:06.513
So why didn't you just say that?

46:11.226 --> 46:14.396
[Holden]   They don't want to learn.
What are we even doing here?

46:14.646 --> 46:16.523
[Tench] Don't make it too complicated.

46:16.773 --> 46:17.983
What's wrong with complicated?

46:18.066 --> 46:20.944
There's complicated
and there's too complicated, Holden.

46:24.156 --> 46:27.075
We used to do this experiment
in social psychology.

46:27.618 --> 46:28.952
Uh-huh. What was that?

46:29.328 --> 46:32.956
You get onto a crowded elevator,
and you face the opposite direction,

46:33.040 --> 46:36.543
the back of the elevator,
and everybody freaks out.

46:37.044 --> 46:40.380
They're uncomfortable
for reasons they can't even articulate.

46:41.465 --> 46:45.803
But if you turn around and face the front,
everybody relaxes.

46:46.386 --> 46:49.014
Okay. Well, how do we do that?

46:51.934 --> 46:53.310
What do we have in common?

46:55.437 --> 46:56.647
What unites us?

46:58.649 --> 47:01.527
What keeps us all awake at night?

47:05.364 --> 47:09.159
-[all groaning]
-Monster. Right?

47:10.118 --> 47:11.537
I think we can all agree.

47:13.622 --> 47:15.457
But what do you really know about him?

47:16.333 --> 47:19.044
Did you know that his mother
was a jailbird and a prostitute?

47:19.419 --> 47:21.088
Did you know when he was ten years old,

47:21.171 --> 47:24.007
she palmed him off
onto his sadistic, Bible-thumping uncle

47:24.091 --> 47:28.679
who beat him within an inch of his life
and taunted him to act like a man?

47:29.513 --> 47:31.473
Charles responded to that
by becoming a pimp

47:31.557 --> 47:34.268
and an armed robber,
and was incarcerated for over 20 years,

47:34.351 --> 47:36.353
where he continued to be brutalized.

47:36.436 --> 47:41.275
In 1967, he was paroled,
during the Summer of Love.

47:42.067 --> 47:43.443
And our nightmare began.

47:44.903 --> 47:47.322
[all groaning, chattering]

47:50.951 --> 47:52.369
-[man] Jesus!
-[man 2] Come on!

47:54.621 --> 47:58.000
Here we have a child who was unwanted,
unloved, regularly beaten,

47:58.083 --> 47:59.835
and repeatedly institutionalized.

47:59.918 --> 48:03.964
Now, might this not have had
some sort of an effect on him?

48:04.631 --> 48:07.050
-He was born that way.
-What way?

48:07.634 --> 48:10.178
-[man] Just bad.
-Can we be a little bit more specific?

48:10.262 --> 48:12.472
-Technically, he didn't kill anybody.
-[murmuring]

48:12.556 --> 48:15.892
Look at those eyes.
How can you not say that dude's evil?

48:15.976 --> 48:19.646
That's a little bit Old Testament,
don't you think?

48:19.730 --> 48:23.483
Good, evil, black, white, it's easy.

48:23.859 --> 48:26.695
But who in this room
has a life that's easy?

48:27.529 --> 48:30.032
Circumstances affect behavior.

48:30.699 --> 48:32.743
When we look at Manson's background,

48:32.826 --> 48:36.288
the real question is,
how could we not have seen this coming?

48:36.371 --> 48:37.331
We did.

48:37.873 --> 48:39.041
[Holden] I'm sorry?

48:39.124 --> 48:42.586
He was institutionalized
because we could see it coming.

48:42.669 --> 48:45.589
Okay, but I'm saying maybe, just maybe,

48:46.131 --> 48:48.967
locking him up his young life
helped make him what he was.

48:49.051 --> 48:50.761
-[man] No.
-What the fuck?

48:50.844 --> 48:53.221
They locked him up
because of what he did.

48:53.305 --> 48:54.765
They already knew what he was.

48:54.848 --> 48:57.934
Okay, guys, I'm not asking anybody
to feel sorry for Charles Manson.

48:58.018 --> 49:00.771
If he were here, I'd shoot him dead.
No one would stop me.

49:00.854 --> 49:01.688
[man] Right.

49:01.772 --> 49:03.982
What Holden's trying to say
is maybe it's both.

49:04.066 --> 49:06.234
The one impacting on the other
in a vicious circle.

49:06.318 --> 49:08.487
Nobody has all the answers.

49:08.570 --> 49:11.490
-We have some answers.
-We should be asking questions.

49:11.573 --> 49:12.824
[man] No shit.

49:12.908 --> 49:15.327
Well, I'll just tell my buddies
in Robbery-Homicide

49:15.410 --> 49:17.663
who were there
when the corpses were found,

49:17.746 --> 49:20.999
that they may have overlooked
a difficult upbringing.

49:21.083 --> 49:22.459
You were LAPD?

49:22.542 --> 49:23.877
Twenty-two years.

49:25.128 --> 49:26.254
You worked Manson?

49:26.338 --> 49:28.548
No, but I knew every single man who did.

49:29.925 --> 49:31.718
How many homicides have you worked?

49:31.802 --> 49:33.804
[audience murmuring]

49:35.472 --> 49:38.350
Figure out who you're talking to
before you tell a sob story

49:38.433 --> 49:40.185
about little Chuckie Manson.

49:40.268 --> 49:42.521
They wrote "pigs" on the wall
in their victims' blood.

49:42.604 --> 49:44.147
They completely missed my point.

49:44.231 --> 49:47.526
In the future, ask if anyone's worked
a case before you bring it up.

49:47.609 --> 49:50.445
-Know your fucking audience.
-Oh, shit.

49:51.405 --> 49:53.699
It's okay, they always do this.

49:53.782 --> 49:55.534
Just be a good listener.

49:55.617 --> 49:56.535
Gentlemen.

49:58.203 --> 49:59.204
Frank McGraw.

50:00.163 --> 50:02.165
I didn't mean to embarrass anybody
back there.

50:02.249 --> 50:03.375
Not a problem.

50:03.458 --> 50:05.544
We're all a little tense around here.

50:05.627 --> 50:09.297
You must have heard about the mother
and child who were murdered recently.

50:09.381 --> 50:12.175
-Ada Jeffries and her boy.
-We've seen reporters.

50:13.385 --> 50:14.970
She was bound,

50:15.053 --> 50:17.347
stabbed repeatedly
about the chest and face.

50:18.014 --> 50:19.266
The boy's throat was cut.

50:19.349 --> 50:22.352
[groans] Rough one.

50:22.436 --> 50:26.273
I don't understand entirely
what you're talking about with psychology.

50:27.649 --> 50:30.068
I don't understand
much of anything anymore.

50:30.152 --> 50:31.737
What's on your mind, Frank?

50:34.030 --> 50:36.616
-I hate to bother.
-No, by all means. Bother us.

50:43.081 --> 50:46.960
When I left Los Angeles,
I thought I'd gone far enough.

50:49.755 --> 50:53.258
Ada was the kind of woman
who wouldn't say boo to a goose.

50:53.800 --> 50:56.553
She came from a deeply religious family
in Arkansas.

50:57.095 --> 50:59.890
When they found out she was pregnant,
they put her out.

51:00.390 --> 51:02.934
She lived in a rooming house
in Libertyville.

51:03.018 --> 51:07.564
No drugs, no alcohol,
never had a brush with the law.

51:08.315 --> 51:10.484
The boy was polite and quiet.

51:11.151 --> 51:13.904
She had him in Sunday school
at the Methodist church.

51:14.237 --> 51:17.407
She would sweep the steps every evening,

51:18.325 --> 51:19.743
just to be of service.

51:21.495 --> 51:22.829
I never met Ada.

51:23.747 --> 51:24.623
Every now and again,

51:24.706 --> 51:27.417
I'd see her and her son walk
along the road into town.

51:28.502 --> 51:29.711
They didn't have a car.

51:32.422 --> 51:34.174
Landlady found the bodies.

51:37.219 --> 51:38.470
They had been dead...

51:40.680 --> 51:41.681
four days.

51:47.938 --> 51:49.773
What people won't do to each other.

51:50.941 --> 51:52.526
Nothing people won't do.

51:54.653 --> 51:55.862
How can we help?

51:58.615 --> 52:01.618
[McGraw]  She was found cuffed
and lashed to the bed.

52:02.244 --> 52:04.538
A broomstick perforated her rectum.

52:05.539 --> 52:07.791
Whoever it was made the boy watch,

52:09.376 --> 52:11.169
then did the same thing to him.

52:12.420 --> 52:13.463
How'd he get in?

52:13.839 --> 52:16.633
Bathroom window.
We think that's how he came and went.

52:17.217 --> 52:18.677
There was no sign of forcible entry.

52:19.427 --> 52:21.513
-No one heard a peep.
-In a rooming house?

52:21.596 --> 52:25.225
My assumption is, he held a knife
to the boy to keep her quiet,

52:26.059 --> 52:27.269
and vice versa.

52:27.352 --> 52:29.729
This falls clearly
into the category of lust murder.

52:29.813 --> 52:31.523
By that I mean it's sexually motivated.

52:31.606 --> 52:34.067
That cannot be about horny.

52:34.151 --> 52:37.904
It's more about sexual gratification
through the annihilation of another.

52:38.238 --> 52:40.991
-Did you find semen?
-Found some on a throw cushion.

52:41.074 --> 52:44.077
It was blood type O.
I know that's not much help.

52:44.160 --> 52:45.912
-[Tench] In the victims?
-[McGraw] No.

52:46.788 --> 52:49.082
-He didn't rape them.
-He could have problems with sex.

52:49.165 --> 52:50.417
That'd be a good bet.

52:50.500 --> 52:52.127
Could narrow things with your suspects.

52:52.210 --> 52:53.753
I don't have suspects.

52:53.837 --> 52:56.798
I don't have fingerprints, shoe prints,

52:56.882 --> 52:58.675
not so much as a single hair.

52:59.342 --> 53:00.176
Well...

53:00.260 --> 53:02.721
The fact that the killer
left nothing behind is interesting.

53:02.804 --> 53:04.848
It must have been premeditated
to a degree.

53:04.931 --> 53:08.101
He had gloves,
he cleaned up after himself.

53:08.184 --> 53:09.728
You think he was stalking her?

53:09.811 --> 53:12.397
-Or she just caught his eye.
-What about the boy?

53:13.023 --> 53:14.024
He was a witness.

53:14.107 --> 53:16.526
There are more expedient ways
to get rid of a witness.

53:16.610 --> 53:18.862
-Why make the boy watch?
-And why sodomize him?

53:18.945 --> 53:20.113
[Holden] That's a good point.

53:20.655 --> 53:23.783
Is this crime about the woman
or about the child?

53:27.120 --> 53:30.040
-You're asking me?
-I was just posing questions.

53:31.333 --> 53:32.751
I get that.

53:32.834 --> 53:34.502
-The broomstick.
-Yeah?

53:34.586 --> 53:37.505
Is it the same broomstick
she used to sweep the church steps?

53:37.589 --> 53:39.716
-What if it is?
-He might not be a congregant,

53:39.799 --> 53:44.012
maybe someone just passing through,
but the church could be significant.

53:44.095 --> 53:45.013
Could be?

53:45.096 --> 53:47.223
[Holden] With the idea of service.

53:48.308 --> 53:52.145
I think that there's a passage in Mark.

53:52.228 --> 53:54.648
Something about the "Son of Man."

53:55.482 --> 53:56.900
I don't follow.

53:56.983 --> 53:59.444
[Holden] All I'm saying is,
the broom may mean something.

53:59.527 --> 54:00.528
What?

54:02.155 --> 54:03.198
I don't know.

54:03.281 --> 54:05.241
It's hard to tell from just the photos.

54:05.325 --> 54:06.701
[scoffs]

54:08.328 --> 54:12.499
This woman was devoted to her child,
tried hard,

54:12.582 --> 54:14.501
and some stranger came along and...

54:16.169 --> 54:19.422
Come on, Agent Ford,
you got fancy methods.

54:19.506 --> 54:23.843
What does a broomstick in the ass
of a dirt poor single mom mean?

54:29.391 --> 54:30.558
I don't know.

54:31.267 --> 54:32.435
You're kidding me.

54:32.519 --> 54:33.687
I don't understand it.

54:34.771 --> 54:37.941
-We can't help you with this.
-We need more time to go over this.

54:38.024 --> 54:42.028
We are in the dark here.
We don't know any more than you do.

54:44.030 --> 54:45.865
How fucking dare you?

54:46.700 --> 54:48.368
I'm sorry we wasted your time.

54:54.666 --> 54:56.793
-Can I get these back to you?
-[scoffs]

55:13.560 --> 55:16.938
-[Don McLean's "Crying" playing]
-♪ Crying ♪

55:17.022 --> 55:19.607
♪ Crying ♪

55:19.691 --> 55:24.446
♪ It's hard to understand ♪

55:26.114 --> 55:31.536
♪ That the touch of your hand ♪

55:31.619 --> 55:33.747
♪ Can start me crying ♪

55:33.830 --> 55:35.665
-In the dark, huh?
-We are.

55:35.749 --> 55:38.501
I have studied everything we have.
I've taken this ride here,

55:38.585 --> 55:40.795
listened to everything
you've been kind enough to teach,

55:40.879 --> 55:43.715
but we're talking about something
we don't understand in the slightest.

55:43.798 --> 55:44.883
I was trying to help you.

55:44.966 --> 55:47.302
If you don't like it,
go back to your college kids

55:47.385 --> 55:48.428
and we'll forget about it.

55:48.511 --> 55:49.888
Ada and her son were killed

55:49.971 --> 55:52.182
for reasons we are simply not equipped
to understand.

55:52.265 --> 55:53.767
It wasn't lust murder.

55:53.850 --> 55:56.644
It wasn't some random thrill killer
who was born bad,

55:56.728 --> 55:59.439
and it wasn't a pantie thief
who wanted to change things up.

55:59.522 --> 56:00.815
It was an aberration.

56:00.899 --> 56:02.901
Let me tell you something
about aberrant behavior.

56:02.984 --> 56:04.235
It's fucking aberrant.

56:04.319 --> 56:06.780
If we understood it, we'd be aberrant too.

56:06.863 --> 56:09.532
Fortunately, it's not incumbent upon us
to write a dissertation.

56:09.616 --> 56:11.159
-Well, maybe we should.
-Why?

56:12.243 --> 56:15.830
Our job is to give him something
he could not have figured out himself.

56:15.914 --> 56:18.541
-I am sticking my neck out for you.
-No disrespect.

56:18.625 --> 56:22.295
At the moment, I don't think we can say
anything to McGraw with any certainty.

56:22.378 --> 56:24.506
Let me ask you something.
Where are you from?

56:26.633 --> 56:29.511
I was born in New York,
but it's kind of a mixed bag.

56:29.594 --> 56:32.722
Okay. Well, that's what you are
right now, a mixed bag.

56:33.223 --> 56:35.850
A little college education,
some experience on the street,

56:35.934 --> 56:38.061
some insight, a lot of horseshit.

56:38.144 --> 56:39.687
I agree with you.

56:39.771 --> 56:42.107
It's been one step forward,
two steps back.

56:42.190 --> 56:44.567
Let me ask you something else.
Do you have a girlfriend?

56:45.527 --> 56:47.987
-I do now, Bill, as it happens.
-Okay.

56:48.071 --> 56:52.075
So next time you're a long way from home
and you flip your shit,

56:52.158 --> 56:55.703
you find a pay phone
and you tell it to your girlfriend.

56:56.454 --> 56:57.539
-Okay?
-Okay.

56:57.622 --> 57:00.500
-How's that sound?
-It sounds okay, Bill.

57:05.713 --> 57:12.178
